---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import NeoCard from '../../components/NeoCard.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Mathematics for Machine Learning - AI/ML Hub">
  <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding-bottom: 5rem;">
    
    <!-- Hero Block -->
    <header class="neo-border neo-shadow bg-yellow" style="padding: 2.5rem 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 3rem; text-align: center; border-width: 3.5px;">
      <span style="font-size: 3rem; display: block; margin-bottom: 1rem;">🧮</span>
      <h1 style="font-size: 2.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0; letter-spacing: -1px; line-height: 1;">Mathematics Foundations</h1>
      <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: bold; color: #1f2937; margin: 0;">
        The hidden engines powering every weight update, gradient descent step, and representation bottleneck.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2.5rem;">
      
      <!-- Intro Section -->
      <section class="neo-border" style="background-color: #fff; padding: 2rem; border-width: 3px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          Why Mathematics in AI/ML?
        </h2>
        <p style="font-size: 1rem; font-weight: bold; color: #374151; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">
          At its core, a machine learning model is simply a parameterized mathematical function. 
          Training a model is the process of adjusting these parameters so the function maps inputs to outputs as accurately as possible. 
          Without mathematics, AI is a black box. Linear algebra structures our high-dimensional data; multivariate calculus enables us to find parameter paths that minimize loss; and probability theory lets us quantify uncertainty and model statistical regularities.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- 1. Linear Algebra Card -->
      <NeoCard color="#a8d5ff" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          1. Linear Algebra: High-Dimensional Containers
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          Linear algebra is the language of machine learning. It allows us to bundle data, operations, and parameters into clean algebraic objects called vectors and matrices.
        </p>
        
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Vector Spaces & Transformations</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              Every data sample (e.g., an image of 28x28 pixels) is a vector in a high-dimensional space (e.g., a 784-dimensional space). 
              A matrix acts as a <strong>linear transformation</strong>—when we multiply a vector by a weight matrix (W), we rotate, stretch, or compress the space itself. 
              This is how neural layers transform input data features into a representation space where classification becomes linearly separable.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Eigenvalues & Eigenvectors</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
              For a square matrix <strong>A</strong>, if there is a non-zero vector <strong>v</strong> such that 
              <code>A·v = λ·v</code> (where λ is a scalar), then <strong>v</strong> is an eigenvector and λ is its eigenvalue. 
              Eigenvectors represent the directions along which the transformation only scales the vector, without changing its direction.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              <strong>PCA (Principal Component Analysis) Intuition:</strong> PCA projects high-dimensional data onto eigenvectors of the data's covariance matrix. 
              The eigenvectors with the largest eigenvalues correspond to the axes containing the highest variance. 
              By discarding components with small eigenvalues, we compress data dimensionality while preserving maximum information!
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- 2. Calculus Card -->
      <NeoCard color="#e9d5ff" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          2. Multivariate Calculus: Navigating Loss Landscapes
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          If linear algebra describes the spaces we operate in, calculus describes how to move through them to optimize performance.
        </p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Partial Derivatives & The Gradient Vector</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
              In machine learning, our loss function <code>L(w₁, w₂, ..., wₙ)</code> depends on millions of weights. 
              A partial derivative <code>∂L / ∂wᵢ</code> tells us how the loss changes when we tweak only the parameter <code>wᵢ</code>.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              The <strong>Gradient Vector</strong> (written as <code>∇L</code>) is a vector containing all these partial derivatives. 
              Crucially, <code>∇L</code> points in the direction of the steepest *increase* in loss. 
              Therefore, by moving in the opposite direction (<code>-∇L</code>), we perform <strong>Gradient Descent</strong> to slide down the landscape towards the minimum.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">The Chain Rule (Backpropagation Backpressure)</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              Deep networks represent nested mathematical composite functions: <code>f(g(h(x)))</code>. 
              To calculate how the final loss changes with respect to a weight in the first layer, we use the <strong>Chain Rule</strong>: 
              <code>dy/dx = (dy/du) · (du/dx)</code>. 
              This product chain of local derivatives allows gradients to flow backwards through layers, establishing the backbone of **Backpropagation**.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- 3. Probability Card -->
      <NeoCard color="#bbf7d0" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          3. Probability & Statistics: Reasoning Under Uncertainty
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          Real-world data is noisy, incomplete, and uncertain. Probability theory provides a rigorous mathematical framework to model this randomness.
        </p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Bayes' Theorem & Classification</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
              Bayes' Theorem tells us how to update our belief in a hypothesis (H) given new evidence (E):
              <code>P(H|E) = [P(E|H) · P(H)] / P(E)</code>.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              In classification, Bayes' Theorem maps input features to class probabilities: 
              <code>P(Class | Features) = [P(Features | Class) · P(Class)] / P(Features)</code>. 
              This is the direct foundation of classifiers like Naive Bayes and establishes the theoretical baseline known as the <strong>Bayes Optimal Classifier</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">MLE (Maximum Likelihood Estimation)</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              How do we fit parameters to a statistical distribution? <strong>MLE</strong> assumes our training samples are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.). 
              We calculate the likelihood function representing the probability of observing our dataset given parameter <code>θ</code>. 
              We then maximize this likelihood (or more easily, maximize the log-likelihood). 
              Crucially, minimizing Mean Squared Error under a Gaussian assumption, or minimizing Binary Cross-Entropy loss under a Bernoulli assumption, is mathematically equivalent to Maximum Likelihood Estimation!
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- Roadmap Back Home -->
      <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a href="/" class="neo-border bg-white neo-hover-raise" style="padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: #000; text-decoration: none; border-width: 3px; box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #000;">
          &larr; Back to Ultimate Brain
        </a>
        <a href="/domains/machine-learning" class="neo-border bg-green neo-hover-raise" style="padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: #000; text-decoration: none; border-width: 3px; box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #000;">
          Machine Learning &rarr;
        </a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
